1
00:00:02,376 --> 00:00:28,300
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:28,718 --> 00:00:33,063
homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble, and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,844 --> 00:00:39,911
So this evening, well, let me tell you what happens tomorrow, and it makes sense.

4
00:00:39,930 --> 00:00:57,932
So tomorrow we carry on till lunchtime, and then because the weather, it should be enough fine tomorrow by the way, the weather gets sort of darkish and cold, we might do just a small sit at two o'clock, but then hopefully we will assault the mountain behind us,

5
00:00:59,531 --> 00:01:00,073
Yeah.

6
00:01:02,976 --> 00:01:03,496
Not this one.

7
00:01:04,138 --> 00:01:04,317
That one.

8
00:01:06,200 --> 00:01:07,162
It's only 300 metres.

9
00:01:07,302 --> 00:01:10,206
It's nothing.

10
00:01:10,325 --> 00:01:12,429
Mark ran up and down it.

11
00:01:12,448 --> 00:01:16,153
He said, no problem.

12
00:01:16,174 --> 00:01:23,022
And then we come back and in the evening, just questions and answers really, whatever discussion comes up.

13
00:01:23,603 --> 00:01:23,703
Okay.

14
00:01:23,724 --> 00:01:28,290
And then on Sunday morning, I do a little finishing ceremony, breakfast and

15
00:01:29,030 --> 00:01:50,650
and then you can escape so this evening really it's just tackling this whole problem of daily life you know how do we take into daily life and just use various ways that the Buddha talked about it

16
00:02:11,538 --> 00:02:40,887
first of all just to get a clear idea of what the Buddha's position is when we compare it to other systems shall we say if we look at Christianity it really centres in upon the morality of things so you know the basic myth about Adam and the apple and

17
00:02:41,051 --> 00:02:46,599
And then because of that initial mistake, everybody suffers and whatnot.

18
00:02:47,161 --> 00:02:55,532
And we've all got this original sin, this sort of thing that has to be wiped.

19
00:02:55,551 --> 00:03:00,699
And then it's a very complicated story about the role of Jesus and stuff like that.

20
00:03:02,262 --> 00:03:06,867
But the basic thing is that we're caught between the devil and God.

21
00:03:08,270 --> 00:03:09,692
And there's a lovely story of Job.

22
00:03:10,145 --> 00:03:20,334
which all of you have read, of course, in which the devil says to God, this fellow Job, of course he loves you.

23
00:03:20,615 --> 00:03:21,955
You've given him everything he's got.

24
00:03:22,475 --> 00:03:26,180
You know, all these wives and kids and all this land and cattle.

25
00:03:27,161 --> 00:03:27,980
He says, you've got to test him.

26
00:03:29,102 --> 00:03:32,145
So God thought, hmm.

27
00:03:32,164 --> 00:03:37,349
So he began to test Job and he killed all his wives and all his kids and

28
00:03:37,853 --> 00:04:04,637
took away all his cattle and he's absolutely devastated and he can't understand why this has happened to him so then we have these Job's comforters they all come basically tell him he must have done something wrong but he hasn't and he can't think what he's done to deserve this catastrophe but the one thing he doesn't lose is faith in God the one thing he doesn't lose is faith in the goodness of God

29
00:04:05,241 --> 00:04:16,439
And eventually God, of course, recognises this trust and gives everything back, a hundredfold and all that.

30
00:04:17,422 --> 00:04:26,896
If you like the Coen brothers, their film A Serious Man is based on Job and it's extraordinarily funny.

31
00:04:28,480 --> 00:04:29,882
Anyway, that's by the way.

32
00:04:31,819 --> 00:05:00,762
the Freud simply took that on to a psychological or psychoanalytic level so with Freud you've got this so for a Christian it's this trying to know what is good and evil good and evil and this battle you see between the temptations of the devil and the invitations of God that's the battle between good and evil

33
00:05:01,637 --> 00:05:27,139
In Freud you get a slightly different model where you've got this poor little ego, for one minute is dragged down by this animal id and constantly castigated by the super ego and the poor ego has to weave a little way between these two opposites and try to find some sort of stability.

34
00:05:29,144 --> 00:05:31,127
I just general, you know.

35
00:05:31,148 --> 00:05:34,495
From the Buddha's point of view, it's a slightly different problem.

36
00:05:34,875 --> 00:05:39,766
Yes, all those things come up in his teaching.

37
00:05:40,187 --> 00:05:46,781
The decision, you know, about what is wholesome and unwholesome, what is skillful, etc.

38
00:05:47,841 --> 00:06:08,331
that the id, these basic desires, that our animal nature drawn to sex and lust and greed and then avarice and all that, all these things are in the Buddha's teachings.

39
00:06:10,716 --> 00:06:15,502
And the desire to seek happiness in

40
00:06:15,802 --> 00:06:18,427
in doing something good, that's all there too, you see.

41
00:06:18,786 --> 00:06:22,512
So it's not as though the Buddha would deny any of that.

42
00:06:22,593 --> 00:06:37,035
In fact, he would say that those who've understood that there is consequence for doing good and doing evil, in other words, the law of karma, they're actually on the path.

43
00:06:37,896 --> 00:06:39,077
They're actually on the path, you see.

44
00:06:39,338 --> 00:06:40,680
That's the basic understanding.

45
00:06:41,132 --> 00:06:53,886
So you see, there were people in his time who would have said, it doesn't matter what you do, you can go down one side of the Ganges and do tremendous compassionate acts and come up the other side murdering and pillaging.

46
00:06:54,225 --> 00:07:00,952
It will make a blind bit of difference because your life is set, it's conditioned, it's fated.

47
00:07:03,014 --> 00:07:08,439
So that would be not in his understanding.

48
00:07:11,862 --> 00:07:21,172
From the Buddha's point of view, the problem is at a slightly deeper level, you might say, as to why do we do these things in the first place.

49
00:07:23,173 --> 00:07:26,937
And there he came across this fundamental delusion about who we are.

50
00:07:27,718 --> 00:07:37,228
Remember that, having decided, having, believing that we are human beings, and heaven's sake, all we want is to be happy,

51
00:07:37,951 --> 00:08:05,291
no matter how you might define it if you ask any human being what they want they say I want to be happy and they might define it in all sorts of different ways but that's what they want to be they want to be happy and that search for happiness leads to this acquisitiveness remember gathering things because the more you have of what you like the happier you seem to be you know the more money in the bank you feel safer etc etc

52
00:08:06,435 --> 00:08:11,442
And anything that undermines any of that, of course, you want to get rid of.

53
00:08:11,562 --> 00:08:12,584
So there's your aversion.

54
00:08:13,345 --> 00:08:15,247
And if it's bigger than you, then you run for it.

55
00:08:15,307 --> 00:08:15,867
There's your fear.

56
00:08:16,208 --> 00:08:29,345
So there's your three basic attitudes of acquisitiveness, aversion and fear arising from the idea that as a human being, I can achieve happiness, permanent happiness.

57
00:08:29,805 --> 00:08:35,633
You can achieve it in little bits, but then it always lets you down, doesn't it?

58
00:08:40,506 --> 00:08:55,179
So, although there is at that level of working with what is unwholesome and wholesome, virtuous and otherwise, at a deeper level it's cutting through the very delusion that's causing it.

59
00:08:56,000 --> 00:08:57,322
That's a slightly different model.

60
00:09:00,845 --> 00:09:09,432
So the accent is on an investigation as to how these things happen, as to how we behave the way we do, you see.

61
00:09:11,184 --> 00:09:15,850
And he wouldn't deny the role of guilt and shame.

62
00:09:17,413 --> 00:09:36,356
He would deny the sort of existential guilt that might be felt within the Christian, Judaic and Muslim tradition where you are fundamentally evil and you can only be saved by God or Jesus or whatever.

63
00:09:37,839 --> 00:09:40,062
But he...

64
00:09:41,222 --> 00:09:43,725
That wouldn't work from his point of view.

65
00:09:44,167 --> 00:09:51,174
But what does work is that when you do something harmful, then you dread consequences.

66
00:09:51,495 --> 00:09:52,216
And there's your dread.

67
00:09:52,797 --> 00:09:53,798
There's your guilt, you see.

68
00:09:54,418 --> 00:09:55,520
Fear of being caught.

69
00:09:58,004 --> 00:09:58,524
And the shame.

70
00:09:58,884 --> 00:10:02,369
Shame is just not living up to your own standards.

71
00:10:02,489 --> 00:10:04,652
Feeling belittled by your own behaviour.

72
00:10:05,173 --> 00:10:08,817
And seeing yourself belittled in other people's eyes because of your behaviour.

73
00:10:09,943 --> 00:10:14,490
So those two things the Buddha actually calls guardians, guardians of society.

74
00:10:15,291 --> 00:10:17,953
He's not saying they're wholesome, but it does stop you doing things.

75
00:10:26,624 --> 00:10:38,719
So you've got this model where on the one part it's an investigation as to our true nature and what should our relationship be to the world.

76
00:10:39,644 --> 00:10:47,833
And on the other part, it's dealing with habits that we've accumulated, developed because of past wrong understanding.

77
00:10:48,794 --> 00:10:51,518
And even present wrong understanding.

78
00:10:51,538 --> 00:10:52,639
And we're still deluded.

79
00:10:54,221 --> 00:11:00,489
Remember that the definition of deluded or delusion is that you don't know where the delusion is.

80
00:11:00,509 --> 00:11:03,913
If you knew where it was, you wouldn't be deluded.

81
00:11:08,095 --> 00:11:11,860
So we've talked a lot about the hindrances and all that sort of stuff.

82
00:11:11,879 --> 00:11:15,203
So maybe it's also time now to talk about these parami.

83
00:11:15,344 --> 00:11:17,025
Parami means to the other shore.

84
00:11:17,626 --> 00:11:25,736
It's translated as perfections, but basically it's the virtues that we need to take us across the water to this island.

85
00:11:26,336 --> 00:11:29,942
So the island the Buddha often uses as an image for Nibbana.

86
00:11:30,341 --> 00:11:34,187
It's something beyond this present life form, you see.

87
00:11:35,331 --> 00:11:43,946
So let me read through them first, and then afterwards I just want to talk a little bit about commitment, you see.

88
00:11:44,927 --> 00:11:46,288
So we have ten qualities.

89
00:11:46,409 --> 00:11:53,520
Now, in the Mahayana they have five, but in Theravada they have ten, which proves that we're better.

90
00:11:57,067 --> 00:12:01,153
Actually, these were compiled later out of the scriptures.

91
00:12:01,893 --> 00:12:04,895
I think as a challenge to Madhyama.

92
00:12:06,057 --> 00:12:08,440
Anyway, these are the purifications, ten leading ones.

93
00:12:08,460 --> 00:12:12,345
So there's the giving, or liberality, generosity.

94
00:12:13,245 --> 00:12:23,056
There's morality, renunciation, wisdom, energy, patience, truthfulness, resolution, loving-kindness, and equanimity.

95
00:12:23,716 --> 00:12:28,962
So obviously it doesn't include every virtue there is, but at least it gives us some sort of platform.

96
00:12:30,427 --> 00:12:47,022
Giving is really the basic virtue the Buddha points to as a starting point because he points out that even thieves can be generous with what they've just taken from you.

97
00:12:47,062 --> 00:12:50,245
They can be very generous to their friends and family.

98
00:12:51,186 --> 00:12:59,472
So generosity is probably one of the easiest things that you can do because it's a matter of giving, you see.

99
00:13:00,482 --> 00:13:05,467
And he always starts his talk to lay people with Dana, with this idea of giving.

100
00:13:06,148 --> 00:13:12,214
And then he talks about the good life, and he talks about being reborn in heavenly realms and all that.

101
00:13:12,394 --> 00:13:15,716
And when he's got his audience, then he hits them with the Four Noble Truths.

102
00:13:18,139 --> 00:13:19,660
He sort of wheedles his way in, you know.

103
00:13:21,282 --> 00:13:27,368
So I want to latch together these three great virtues, gratitude...

104
00:13:28,445 --> 00:13:30,908
generosity and renunciation.

105
00:13:34,793 --> 00:13:39,177
When we consider what we've received, you see, gratitude arises.

106
00:13:40,298 --> 00:13:43,803
And it's a lovely feeling, isn't it, gratitude, thankfulness.

107
00:13:45,645 --> 00:13:51,533
And if you go through your life and instead of thinking of how horrible everybody's been to you,

108
00:13:51,967 --> 00:14:09,485
a terrible society and all that, and instead you go through and make a list of all the things that you've been given, even this life by our mothers, then very slowly the balance moves, generally speaking, towards gratitude rather than grudge.

109
00:14:11,849 --> 00:14:19,056
And what gratitude does, of course, it fills a heart with the desire to repay, to do something in return.

110
00:14:20,167 --> 00:14:28,817
And often you can't do it to the people who've done you good because either they've moved on or you've lost contacts, etc.

111
00:14:32,082 --> 00:14:36,327
So therefore you move it towards an attitude of giving.

112
00:14:37,350 --> 00:14:47,423
And it might not be giving what you received, but it's just knowing that gratitude impels you to be generous one way or the other, you see.

113
00:14:49,495 --> 00:14:53,340
And generosity is either of our wealth or our time.

114
00:14:54,140 --> 00:14:56,624
You see, isn't it?

115
00:14:56,644 --> 00:15:02,511
Now, the interesting thing is that every time you give something, you're giving something up.

116
00:15:02,532 --> 00:15:05,254
Because you could have used it for yourself.

117
00:15:05,274 --> 00:15:08,679
So when you make a donation to a cause, you know, you could have used it.

118
00:15:09,019 --> 00:15:11,163
Well, to have a good time.

119
00:15:11,182 --> 00:15:18,371
And every time you give your time for the benefit of somebody else, well, you could have used it to have a good time.

120
00:15:18,773 --> 00:15:22,980
You might have had a good time helping them, but it wasn't for you.

121
00:15:23,520 --> 00:15:25,826
So there's that renunciation, you see.

122
00:15:26,407 --> 00:15:35,643
And sometimes, when you give, you can sometimes push the giving just a little bit so that it hurts a little.

123
00:15:36,544 --> 00:15:40,191
Because that little bit of hurt means you're stretching your idea of renunciation.

124
00:15:43,394 --> 00:16:12,186
I think parents with children obviously have a wonderful opportunity because it's just like you've got to keep stretching they demand and you've got to keep stretching out towards them, giving moise so these three virtues are intimately connected gratitude, generosity and renunciation

125
00:16:12,756 --> 00:16:16,822
Now, renunciation, remember, mustn't be confused with self-mortification.

126
00:16:17,703 --> 00:16:25,095
In self-mortification, what we mean by that in Buddhist terms is that you sort of believe the body is at fault.

127
00:16:26,116 --> 00:16:35,711
And you're almost denying the body its desires because the body is leading you into wrongdoing.

128
00:16:36,972 --> 00:16:38,274
So you blame the body.

129
00:16:38,659 --> 00:16:43,825
So, for instance, if you had a problem with alcohol, you're blaming the body, you know.

130
00:16:43,845 --> 00:16:47,288
So, it's a case of recognizing that that's not what renunciation is.

131
00:16:47,327 --> 00:16:52,173
Renunciation, in Buddhist understanding, is to give something up to see your attachment.

132
00:16:53,794 --> 00:16:57,798
And you don't know how attached you are to something until what you have is gone.

133
00:16:59,660 --> 00:17:08,328
And then there comes all these things that we've talked about with attachment, you know, the grief and all that.

134
00:17:09,202 --> 00:17:18,494
So whenever we're generous, that's an opportunity to reflect on, you know, to actually make it a pure act of generosity.

135
00:17:19,635 --> 00:17:22,359
So sometimes we, there are all sorts of reasons for giving.

136
00:17:22,539 --> 00:17:25,864
You might give, I mean, you might do something for a business reason.

137
00:17:26,365 --> 00:17:27,145
You know, that's fine.

138
00:17:27,586 --> 00:17:28,548
There's nothing wrong with that.

139
00:17:29,628 --> 00:17:34,496
You know, you buy somebody a drink so that they will, you know, sign the contract.

140
00:17:34,635 --> 00:17:36,357
Well, what's the problem with that?

141
00:17:37,182 --> 00:17:42,048
But it's not generosity in a spiritual sense.

142
00:17:42,067 --> 00:17:43,990
We buy presents at Christmas for each other.

143
00:17:44,109 --> 00:17:46,272
You know, a bottle of wine and somebody buys you cheese.

144
00:17:46,814 --> 00:17:48,756
You know, a pair of socks for everything.

145
00:17:48,776 --> 00:17:52,380
So... And it's just an exchange of goods.

146
00:17:52,401 --> 00:17:54,462
I mean, this goes back to ancient times.

147
00:17:55,023 --> 00:17:58,807
Kings exchanged goods as a way of just, you know, creating a certain friendship.

148
00:17:59,068 --> 00:18:02,031
But that's not generosity in the spiritual sense.

149
00:18:02,292 --> 00:18:03,153
But there's nothing wrong with it.

150
00:18:03,673 --> 00:18:05,957
It has its purpose...

151
00:18:06,156 --> 00:18:07,278
In our relationships.

152
00:18:09,862 --> 00:18:11,384
The generosity we're talking about.

153
00:18:11,704 --> 00:18:13,686
Is giving for the sake of the other.

154
00:18:14,048 --> 00:18:14,969
Not for any reason.

155
00:18:15,009 --> 00:18:17,011
Not for any purpose of return.

156
00:18:17,932 --> 00:18:19,836
So we have to be careful.

157
00:18:19,875 --> 00:18:21,478
When we give something.

158
00:18:21,498 --> 00:18:22,479
And this is what we mean.

159
00:18:22,599 --> 00:18:25,403
This is why this reflection is important.

160
00:18:26,444 --> 00:18:27,606
So when you give something.

161
00:18:28,307 --> 00:18:30,170
You give it for the benefit of the other.

162
00:18:30,470 --> 00:18:33,134
And when that suffuses your heart.

163
00:18:33,233 --> 00:18:35,037
When that suffuses your intention.

164
00:18:35,076 --> 00:18:35,978
Your intention is.

165
00:18:36,211 --> 00:19:01,914
complete and whole that's what's in your mind you're giving it for their benefit that's when you give you see so that the action supports the intention and that's your conditioning okay and we're conditioning ourselves to just give to just give now you have to be careful because after you've done that you see these little voices come up yeah you're truly a generous person

166
00:19:03,396 --> 00:19:10,425
So you point to that and you say, ah, no, no, no, Mara, no, you weren't there, you weren't there.

167
00:19:10,526 --> 00:19:13,789
Or one of these little underlying things, there's too much, get some back.

168
00:19:16,432 --> 00:19:27,767
Or there's sometimes you don't reflect upon somebody asking you, like, you know, decorations, you had all this decoration, it went on for days and days.

169
00:19:28,117 --> 00:19:32,701
And, you know, if somebody comes along and says, oh, yeah, I'll come along.

170
00:19:32,741 --> 00:19:34,864
And then they go and think, I don't want to decorate.

171
00:19:34,884 --> 00:19:38,488
You know.

172
00:19:38,508 --> 00:19:40,930
And then they phone up and say they're not feeling very well.

173
00:19:44,413 --> 00:19:46,095
And, I mean, you can't blame.

174
00:19:46,174 --> 00:19:47,276
It's not bad to blame people.

175
00:19:47,536 --> 00:19:50,980
But it just shows that often we give without a certain reflection.

176
00:19:52,721 --> 00:19:56,724
But often, and we're coming to truthfulness, it's defined as doing what you say you're going to do.

177
00:19:58,949 --> 00:20:10,143
Even if it hurts, because when you do something that you said you were going to do, and then you didn't want to do it, and you make yourself do it, and it teaches you, you know, next time you'll be just a bit more careful to say yes.

178
00:20:11,845 --> 00:20:13,788
You don't want to make the same mistake again.

179
00:20:15,170 --> 00:20:22,719
So this whole area of giving, it's reflecting on it, you see, when you give it.

180
00:20:22,940 --> 00:20:28,787
And of course, you can do that with Christmas presents.

181
00:20:29,746 --> 00:20:59,532
even though at the back of your mind you know that if you didn't give it that would be the end of your friendship the fact is that you can put that to the side and give something for the person's benefit so remember that intention is crucial your intention is crucial and the purer it is the better and of course don't forget you can be generous to yourself we have to also learn that I am also worthy of generosity

182
00:20:59,767 --> 00:21:02,351
And sometimes you have to look after yourselves.

183
00:21:02,991 --> 00:21:03,692
So the Buddha did.

184
00:21:04,073 --> 00:21:13,047
I mean, here he is, he's liberated from suffering, he says he doesn't suffer, and yet he goes off into the forest to meditate.

185
00:21:13,528 --> 00:21:15,510
And so they ask him, why do you do that?

186
00:21:15,530 --> 00:21:18,535
You know, you're liberated now.

187
00:21:18,717 --> 00:21:23,564
He says, no, I do it for my own quiet abiding and as a good example to others.

188
00:21:23,865 --> 00:21:26,868
But notice, the first thing is my quiet abiding.

189
00:21:27,109 --> 00:21:31,256
Like he's had enough of all these questions and grabbing his potty.

190
00:21:31,675 --> 00:21:35,122
So he's off and he's, oh God, a bit of peace and quiet.

191
00:21:36,483 --> 00:21:42,732
And he does it also to show, to be an example to others.

192
00:21:44,434 --> 00:21:50,760
When you feed yourself, you see, when you eat yourself, you know, really say, really acknowledge that this is for our benefit.

193
00:21:50,780 --> 00:21:51,862
It's not for my benefit.

194
00:21:51,922 --> 00:21:59,730
I'm eating this for my benefit so that I can, you know, continue to live and live the spiritual life.

195
00:22:00,590 --> 00:22:10,641
So it's very, you've got to be careful that you don't get into this thing about helping others and leave yourself out.

196
00:22:10,661 --> 00:22:12,423
Because eventually it works against you.

197
00:22:12,462 --> 00:22:14,424
I mean, you get this burnout business, you know.

198
00:22:17,324 --> 00:22:25,136
And giving somebody who's a do-gooder.

199
00:22:25,416 --> 00:22:26,538
See, that's the other side of it.

200
00:22:27,319 --> 00:22:32,828
So a do-gooder, in my definition, is somebody who does you the good they want to do you.

201
00:22:34,471 --> 00:22:35,473
Whether you want it or not.

202
00:22:38,038 --> 00:22:40,682
And people like that come from a good heart.

203
00:22:41,017 --> 00:22:43,481
But they're not really standing in your shoes.

204
00:22:43,582 --> 00:22:46,929
They're not really looking at the world from what you want to do.

205
00:22:46,989 --> 00:22:51,278
They think, well, this is what's good for you.

206
00:22:54,384 --> 00:22:57,590
And it can be a real pain.

207
00:22:58,599 --> 00:23:12,056
So, you know, the example I give is that somebody's ill, so you take them grapes and soup or something, you know, and they say, you know, thank you very much, but I really couldn't eat, you know, the soup, you see.

208
00:23:12,656 --> 00:23:17,481
And inside your mind you say, you know, I've just spent two hours making this bloody soup.

209
00:23:18,864 --> 00:23:20,365
They say, you could do something for me.

210
00:23:20,826 --> 00:23:21,948
Oh, yeah, very good.

211
00:23:21,968 --> 00:23:23,088
Could you clean my toilet?

212
00:23:24,924 --> 00:23:28,949
I think I'd better clean your toilet.

213
00:23:28,969 --> 00:23:30,150
I came here to offer you soup.

214
00:23:33,053 --> 00:23:39,700
So, you can always catch yourself, you know, when you're doing this good and then you find, you find actually you're being a do-gooder.

215
00:23:41,441 --> 00:23:43,303
So, how do we get beyond that?

216
00:23:43,383 --> 00:23:44,023
It's very simple.

217
00:23:44,084 --> 00:23:45,464
You ask the person what they want.

218
00:23:47,207 --> 00:23:53,413
You know, you don't presume on anything at all.

219
00:23:53,680 --> 00:23:56,483
Giving itself is a really...

220
00:23:57,265 --> 00:23:59,970
Generosity is really crucial in our practice.

221
00:24:00,730 --> 00:24:02,894
And it's a form of love, of course.

222
00:24:03,034 --> 00:24:06,219
Generosity is just there.

223
00:24:07,480 --> 00:24:13,951
And, you know, it's lovely when you see these... What do they call it?

224
00:24:13,990 --> 00:24:15,894
Sports for...

225
00:24:16,013 --> 00:24:16,734
Sport relief.

226
00:24:17,036 --> 00:24:18,938
Yeah, sport relief and comic relief.

227
00:24:19,199 --> 00:24:21,982
They raise masses of money and it's really quite...

228
00:24:22,839 --> 00:24:29,509
Well, it's quite uplifting to know that people were prepared to, you know, to give, you know, for these causes.

229
00:24:29,568 --> 00:24:30,190
Really wonderful.

230
00:24:34,015 --> 00:24:37,779
So that sort of covers three of them anyway.

231
00:24:38,400 --> 00:24:43,887
So it's the giving and the, I mean, gratitude isn't mentioned here, but it's definitely something.

232
00:24:44,367 --> 00:24:49,454
Meister Eckhart, whom some of you might know, the 13th century mystic, who's very close to Buddhism,

233
00:24:49,553 --> 00:24:53,057
If you read his stuff, it's very, very close to the Buddha's understanding.

234
00:24:54,259 --> 00:24:58,503
He says, if you were to say thank you all the time, that would be enough.

235
00:25:00,085 --> 00:25:04,671
That's how important he thought gratitude was.

236
00:25:05,571 --> 00:25:06,472
Brian does it, doesn't he?

237
00:25:06,492 --> 00:25:07,974
Just for today, I will be thankful.

238
00:25:09,096 --> 00:25:13,820
Even he's caught on to it.

239
00:25:14,021 --> 00:25:15,462
So, it's something to reflect on.

240
00:25:17,085 --> 00:25:18,346
So, we've done the renunciation.

241
00:25:18,386 --> 00:25:19,407
Renunciation is

242
00:25:19,625 --> 00:25:31,042
You know, and it's just catching yourself these sneaky little selfishnesses.

243
00:25:31,063 --> 00:25:34,848
You know, where you take just the bigger piece of cake.

244
00:25:35,049 --> 00:25:35,891
You know what I mean?

245
00:25:36,692 --> 00:25:41,179
You take that extra toffee, you know.

246
00:25:41,199 --> 00:25:43,061
And then you just catch yourself.

247
00:25:44,505 --> 00:25:45,987
And then you hate the person who gets it, of course.

248
00:25:49,138 --> 00:25:51,061
So, renunciation.

249
00:25:52,525 --> 00:25:54,807
Morality, well, we've talked a lot about that.

250
00:25:57,772 --> 00:26:06,067
It's again, morality here, the Buddha's actually meaning just the basic things that you determine, not to go there, that's all.

251
00:26:07,469 --> 00:26:09,152
Wisdom, well, we've talked about that.

252
00:26:09,511 --> 00:26:13,739
So this is more of a mental, of a mind.

253
00:26:13,799 --> 00:26:15,923
So a lot of these are heart things, like giving.

254
00:26:16,730 --> 00:26:18,231
And renunciation and patience.

255
00:26:18,672 --> 00:26:19,933
But wisdom is coming from.

256
00:26:19,993 --> 00:26:21,434
This wisdom within us.

257
00:26:22,316 --> 00:26:23,778
This understanding.

258
00:26:23,798 --> 00:26:24,818
The faculty of wisdom.

259
00:26:25,138 --> 00:26:26,721
Which is not to be confused with intellect.

260
00:26:26,760 --> 00:26:28,843
Remember.

261
00:26:29,703 --> 00:26:30,605
There's a lovely story.

262
00:26:30,625 --> 00:26:32,948
I always forget the name of the monk.

263
00:26:33,409 --> 00:26:35,411
But in those days remember.

264
00:26:35,770 --> 00:26:36,751
They didn't write things down.

265
00:26:36,791 --> 00:26:37,472
They remembered them.

266
00:26:38,374 --> 00:26:40,576
And this poor monk he said.

267
00:26:40,596 --> 00:26:43,359
When he learnt a new stanza.

268
00:26:43,579 --> 00:26:44,661
Of the Buddha's teachings.

269
00:26:45,020 --> 00:26:46,482
It would knock the one he's just learnt.

270
00:26:46,732 --> 00:27:15,558
out of his head so his brothers advised him to leave the monastic life said you know you're not going to get anywhere so the Buddha hearing this went to see him and he gave him a very simple exercise of rubbing a piece of cloth and wiping his face with a clean cloth and just saying impermanence impermanence impermanence and he became fully liberated just like that it didn't work for everybody it didn't work for me

271
00:27:16,196 --> 00:27:21,423
But it's a different faculty.

272
00:27:21,462 --> 00:27:22,364
It's not the intellect.

273
00:27:22,443 --> 00:27:25,326
It's not about understanding something.

274
00:27:25,587 --> 00:27:29,991
There's one man called Putika.

275
00:27:30,012 --> 00:27:30,633
What's his name?

276
00:27:31,453 --> 00:27:33,236
Empty Putika.

277
00:27:33,256 --> 00:27:38,321
There's another monk and he can explain the Dharma wonderfully.

278
00:27:38,741 --> 00:27:40,964
But the Buddha calls him Empty Putila.

279
00:27:41,204 --> 00:27:41,585
Empty.

280
00:27:42,046 --> 00:27:43,448
Because he's not coming from experience.

281
00:27:43,528 --> 00:27:44,489
He's coming from his intellect.

282
00:27:44,548 --> 00:27:45,630
He's coming from understanding.

283
00:27:46,926 --> 00:28:16,781
and people like that really have a big problem because they really believe that because they've really understood something that therefore they've actually truly experienced it so that's a lot to do with our honesty as well you see there's another little story about a teacher and all his students become fully liberated

284
00:28:17,740 --> 00:28:18,480
And he isn't.

285
00:28:18,500 --> 00:28:20,363
And he thinks, oh, I can't understand this.

286
00:28:22,305 --> 00:28:28,651
And so he goes off and he asks them, you know, he said, you know, do you think you could help me?

287
00:28:29,112 --> 00:28:32,174
And what the student realises is that his teacher's very conceited.

288
00:28:33,215 --> 00:28:35,719
So he says, well, I can't really help you.

289
00:28:35,999 --> 00:28:38,141
Why don't you go and see somebody else?

290
00:28:38,501 --> 00:28:42,665
Eventually, one of his students tells him to go and see this little boy.

291
00:28:42,705 --> 00:28:47,510
So you can imagine that's a bit humiliating, you know, how to become liberated

292
00:28:48,013 --> 00:28:50,356
So the little boy takes him off to an anthill.

293
00:28:50,738 --> 00:28:54,041
Now, in the east, when the ants have left, it's often the abode of a snake.

294
00:28:55,463 --> 00:29:05,017
And so the little boy says, if a snake lives in that anthill and there are six holes, how do you get him to come out?

295
00:29:06,199 --> 00:29:11,046
He said, well, you just stop up five holes and he'll come out through the sixth.

296
00:29:11,566 --> 00:29:12,688
He said, that's what you've got to do.

297
00:29:13,444 --> 00:29:22,292
In other words, through the senses, the six senses, by stopping five senses and just watching the mind, then you begin to understand, you see.

298
00:29:22,432 --> 00:29:27,897
Well, of course, as all these stories go, in no length of time, the teacher was fully liberated.

299
00:29:30,420 --> 00:29:34,263
So, don't get confused with understanding.

300
00:29:34,304 --> 00:29:36,806
The Buddha actually talks about three levels of understanding.

301
00:29:37,146 --> 00:29:42,050
The level of just hearing something, being inspired by it, understanding it,

302
00:29:42,402 --> 00:30:12,307
but unable really to repeat it because it's not become your own intellectual knowledge and then once it has become your own understanding you can talk about it but then at a deeper level it has to be realized so you can talk about impermanence till the cows come home but have we actually experienced it at the level of me arising and passing away so that's the wisdom bit

303
00:30:12,912 --> 00:30:13,512
Energy.

304
00:30:13,553 --> 00:30:19,260
Energy... What's the other word?

305
00:30:19,320 --> 00:30:19,641
Effort.

306
00:30:20,962 --> 00:30:23,185
Yeah, you've got to be careful with this effort business.

307
00:30:23,626 --> 00:30:34,662
Remember that, normally speaking, our effort is in trying to do something, trying to achieve something, which is perfectly all right in the world.

308
00:30:36,325 --> 00:30:38,768
But when we come to our meditation...

309
00:30:39,067 --> 00:30:43,012
It's important to realize that the effort is just to be aware.

310
00:30:43,614 --> 00:30:50,823
Once you start looking for something or trying to attain something, then you normally end up in a hole.

311
00:30:51,223 --> 00:31:03,519
Because even if you're not fully aware of it, there is some concept at the back of the mind driving this sense of wanting to achieve something.

312
00:31:03,539 --> 00:31:05,041
So be careful with effort.

313
00:31:05,967 --> 00:31:07,107
Just keep reminding yourself.

314
00:31:07,628 --> 00:31:09,751
My teacher used to say, your job is just to watch.

315
00:31:10,011 --> 00:31:11,233
Your job is just to be aware.

316
00:31:17,121 --> 00:31:18,962
Patience.

317
00:31:19,304 --> 00:31:22,607
The Buddha says this is the highest form of ascetic practice.

318
00:31:22,627 --> 00:31:35,163
So if you think of ascetic practice as, you know, fasting for long times, or in certain practices, you've seen these...

319
00:31:36,071 --> 00:31:45,823
ascetics in the East, even the early Christian desert ascetics, you know, sort of, like for instance, just holding up their arm in the air till it withers.

320
00:31:46,083 --> 00:31:46,844
You've seen that one?

321
00:31:47,124 --> 00:31:47,805
Have you seen that one?

322
00:31:47,944 --> 00:31:48,986
Yeah.

323
00:31:49,006 --> 00:31:51,469
So these sort of heavy ascetic practices.

324
00:31:52,770 --> 00:31:57,455
He says actually the greatest of all ascetic practices is patience.

325
00:31:57,476 --> 00:32:03,041
So patience is just a willingness to bear, you know, forbearance.

326
00:32:04,355 --> 00:32:16,130
not only just our own internal pains and stuff, just not to get angry with things, not to be irritated, but of course with situations and other people.

327
00:32:17,491 --> 00:32:22,018
So that patience is one of his great virtues.

328
00:32:23,400 --> 00:32:34,294
And he gives the example of someone who says, if bandits came along and cut you from limb to limb, if at any time you felt hatred,

329
00:32:34,865 --> 00:32:38,249
or a grudge against them, you would be no disciple of mine.

330
00:32:38,608 --> 00:32:42,994
That's a bit tough, isn't it?

331
00:32:43,015 --> 00:32:51,904
When I told this one, somebody said, yeah, the Buddha had a great sense of humour.

332
00:32:51,924 --> 00:32:56,269
But patience is just a great virtue, isn't it?

333
00:32:56,289 --> 00:32:59,894
Patience.

334
00:32:59,913 --> 00:33:00,595
Truthfulness.

335
00:33:01,175 --> 00:33:04,720
Here it's defined as, if you say you're going to do something, do it.

336
00:33:06,521 --> 00:33:12,250
But I mean you can stretch that also to being careful as to what you say.

337
00:33:12,289 --> 00:33:16,275
Even exaggeration is a small level of untruthfulness.

338
00:33:17,355 --> 00:33:19,298
It's not being absolutely correct.

339
00:33:21,141 --> 00:33:23,845
Exaggerating both negatively and positively.

340
00:33:27,809 --> 00:33:28,932
And then there's resolution.

341
00:33:29,231 --> 00:33:31,034
So that's what we were doing today, resolution.

342
00:33:31,115 --> 00:33:33,778
Resolution is just that real commitment.

343
00:33:34,130 --> 00:33:44,000
In the Buddha's life it manifested in his resolution to sit under the tree and sort of work the problem out either to the point of death or you actually work it out.

344
00:33:44,961 --> 00:33:47,623
So you have to be pretty resolved to do something like that.

345
00:33:54,230 --> 00:34:01,757
What I normally say is that say a course, you come on a course that you commit yourself to that course completely, right?

346
00:34:02,632 --> 00:34:03,373
Acceptance.

347
00:34:03,393 --> 00:34:07,298
You've always got to put a little ex-clause in because you might go overboard.

348
00:34:07,637 --> 00:34:11,563
Accept in emergency or extraordinary circumstance.

349
00:34:11,603 --> 00:34:15,088
Of course, you're going to define extraordinary circumstance in all sorts of ways.

350
00:34:15,648 --> 00:34:24,579
But the problem with making too hard a decision is that even when all the signs are you should stop, you don't.

351
00:34:25,081 --> 00:34:26,603
And then you do yourself damage, you see.

352
00:34:28,144 --> 00:34:32,250
I know somebody who kept sitting and sitting with knees...

353
00:34:32,416 --> 00:34:34,197
you know, with these knees business, you know.

354
00:34:35,780 --> 00:34:41,425
And the teachers, my teacher actually, the Burmese would just say, watch the breath.

355
00:34:43,166 --> 00:34:47,552
You know, sit, just watch the, you know, watch the pain, see.

356
00:34:47,572 --> 00:34:48,773
Unfortunately, she damaged her knees.

357
00:34:51,215 --> 00:34:52,797
So you have to be, you have to be slightly careful.

358
00:34:54,719 --> 00:34:57,541
You have to go, you have to really suffer if you want to damage your knees, by the way.

359
00:34:58,023 --> 00:35:00,144
You know, it doesn't come with just a little bit of pain.

360
00:35:01,728 --> 00:35:02,628
You've got to work at it.

361
00:35:04,710 --> 00:35:06,333
Then there's loving kindness, metta.

362
00:35:06,673 --> 00:35:16,284
The Buddha often uses metta to mean all forms of love, which includes compassion and sympathetic joy.

363
00:35:16,344 --> 00:35:23,092
Remember, rejoicing in someone, others, good fortune or success as our own.

364
00:35:23,291 --> 00:35:27,135
Don't forget, all these things have to be also directed towards ourselves.

365
00:35:29,338 --> 00:35:30,300
And then equanimity.

366
00:35:31,157 --> 00:36:00,338
equanimity all these virtues do have their obvious enemy their straight enemy and their subtle enemy so with love the obvious enemy is hatred but the more subtle enemy is attachment and you can always tell when you're coming from attachment because you tend to be not listening to the other person or not taking their view or their desire on

367
00:36:01,077 --> 00:36:05,121
And then you tend to get upset because they're not doing what you want to do.

368
00:36:06,744 --> 00:36:09,788
You get irritated, you get bored with them, all that sort of stuff.

369
00:36:10,047 --> 00:36:17,998
Whenever you feel negative about somebody, especially if you have a close relation to them, then you know that's a sign of attachment.

370
00:36:18,818 --> 00:36:24,065
It's always coming from me rather than them or us.

371
00:36:25,927 --> 00:36:27,489
It doesn't mean to say that...

372
00:36:28,059 --> 00:36:31,304
You've got to be careful with that because you don't want to get abused.

373
00:36:32,365 --> 00:36:34,288
You've also got to take yourself into account.

374
00:36:36,530 --> 00:36:37,572
Anyway, it's a tricky area.

375
00:36:37,592 --> 00:36:38,474
I haven't got time.

376
00:36:40,637 --> 00:36:43,059
I'm going on and on about that one.

377
00:36:43,239 --> 00:36:51,251
But equanimity, of course, is confusion, just to get lost in something.

378
00:36:51,630 --> 00:36:54,675
But its most subtle enemy is this indifference.

379
00:36:55,262 --> 00:36:57,286
Where you're standing away too much.

380
00:36:57,445 --> 00:37:01,150
You're standing away too much.

381
00:37:02,172 --> 00:37:03,813
There was a woman came to see me.

382
00:37:03,833 --> 00:37:10,563
She said that every time she came out of meditation at home, her partner accused her of being cold, you see.

383
00:37:11,364 --> 00:37:15,190
So I said to her, well, do you do any metta when you finish your practice?

384
00:37:15,230 --> 00:37:15,550
She said no.

385
00:37:16,811 --> 00:37:18,414
I said, well, that's what you've got to do.

386
00:37:18,434 --> 00:37:20,958
I said, you know, when you sit, you want to be cool.

387
00:37:20,998 --> 00:37:22,260
You want to be equanimous.

388
00:37:22,280 --> 00:37:23,181
You want to be distant.

389
00:37:23,222 --> 00:37:25,204
You want to be able to investigate.

390
00:37:25,965 --> 00:37:27,648
But somehow you've got to re-engage.

391
00:37:28,068 --> 00:37:29,650
You've got to re-engage with the world.

392
00:37:30,072 --> 00:37:33,257
And you do that through the practice of metta.

393
00:37:33,277 --> 00:37:34,778
Anyway, she didn't come back.

394
00:37:37,782 --> 00:37:40,827
Either he gave up on her or she practiced a bit of metta.

395
00:37:42,748 --> 00:37:47,293
So let me read out the way that it says in the commentaries.

396
00:37:48,695 --> 00:38:00,628
As a great being, so that's often a synonym for somebody who is attempting to become fully liberated, or an enlightened being.

397
00:38:01,969 --> 00:38:10,478
Are concerned with the welfare of living beings, not tolerating the suffering of beings, wishing long duration to the higher states of happiness of beings.

398
00:38:10,913 --> 00:38:13,516
and being impartial and just to all beings.

399
00:38:13,655 --> 00:38:21,465
Therefore, they give alms to all beings so that they may be happy without investigating whether they are worthy or not.

400
00:38:23,407 --> 00:38:26,711
By avoiding to do them any harm, they observe morality.

401
00:38:27,393 --> 00:38:31,918
In order to bring morality to perfection, they train themselves in renunciation.

402
00:38:32,960 --> 00:38:38,507
And in order to understand clearly what is beneficial or injurious to beings, they purify their wisdom.

403
00:38:39,532 --> 00:38:44,719
For the sake of the welfare and happiness of others, they constantly exert their energy.

404
00:38:44,739 --> 00:38:52,128
Though having become heroes through utmost energy, they are nevertheless full of forbearance towards the manifold failings of beings.

405
00:38:52,789 --> 00:38:56,996
And once they have promised to give or do something, they do not break their promise.

406
00:38:58,177 --> 00:39:04,525
With unshakable resolution, they work for the will and welfare of beings.

407
00:39:05,106 --> 00:39:08,190
And with unshakable kindness, they are helpful to all,

408
00:39:08,490 --> 00:39:13,338
And by reason of their equanimity, they do not expect anything in return.

409
00:39:14,981 --> 00:39:15,681
There we are.

410
00:39:15,702 --> 00:39:17,284
That's a nice little standard for us.

411
00:39:19,447 --> 00:39:29,141
So that's the, you know, just the little reflections on these paramis, these virtues or perfections that we ought to develop.

412
00:39:30,583 --> 00:39:32,306
And the other thing is commitment.

413
00:39:32,626 --> 00:39:33,367
So...

414
00:39:35,103 --> 00:39:40,409
It really is a case of committing yourself to a daily practice.

415
00:39:40,429 --> 00:39:40,909
Morning.

416
00:39:42,251 --> 00:39:44,954
It's important because that sets the weather vane.

417
00:39:45,016 --> 00:39:50,563
It sort of reminds you the level of awareness and consciousness you want to try and maintain throughout the day.

418
00:39:53,545 --> 00:40:01,275
And then to practice that loving kindness to re-engage with the world straight after that, you see.

419
00:40:02,036 --> 00:40:02,797
So that's important.

420
00:40:03,452 --> 00:40:06,322
And then in the evening, that's the other time, really.

421
00:40:07,748 --> 00:40:12,766
Specifically when you come back from work or definitely before you eat.

422
00:40:13,268 --> 00:40:14,592
After you eat, you just fall asleep.

423
00:40:15,400 --> 00:40:17,623
And the reason there is really to just sit.

424
00:40:17,844 --> 00:40:19,907
And remember, you don't always have to sit in posture.

425
00:40:20,568 --> 00:40:24,717
It is a good thing to sit in posture because it does help the awakeness.

426
00:40:24,737 --> 00:40:27,481
But there, you're just letting the day come through.

427
00:40:27,802 --> 00:40:35,375
So irritations and anxieties and all these things that have been happening during the day, just let them arise and pass away.

428
00:40:35,476 --> 00:40:37,579
So let them pass.

429
00:40:37,599 --> 00:40:39,061
There's all the cleansing, you see.

430
